== Career Progression Pathways

=== Entry Point: Analyst (0-2 years)

*Typical Background*
- Bachelor's degree in Commerce, Finance, Economics, or related field (minimum)
- Strong academic record (Distinction/High Distinction average expected)
- Relevant internships (investment banking, corporate finance, Big Four transaction services)
- Some firms prefer Honours degrees or postgraduate qualifications
- Extra-curricular leadership (university clubs, case competitions) valued

*Initial Development Focus*
- Mastering technical skills (Excel, PowerPoint, financial modelling)
- Learning transaction processes and deal mechanics
- Building industry knowledge and market awareness
- Developing professional maturity and commercial judgment
- Understanding client service excellence standards

*Key Milestones in First 2 Years*
- Leading model building independently by Month 6-9
- Taking ownership of pitch book sections by Month 9-12
- Managing data room processes by Month 12-15
- Developing sector expertise in 1-2 industries
- Building relationships with senior bankers

=== Year 2-3: Senior Analyst / Associate

*Promotion Indicators*
- Consistent technical excellence and accuracy
- Ability to work independently with minimal supervision
- Strong commercial awareness and judgment
- Positive client feedback and team collaboration
- Demonstrated commitment through demanding periods

*Expanding Responsibilities*
- Greater client interaction and meeting participation
- Taking ownership of work stream within transactions (e.g., "you own the valuation work")
- Mentoring and reviewing junior analyst work
- Contributing to pitch strategy and transaction structuring
- Project managing smaller deals end-to-end

*MBA Decision Point*
Many analysts pursue MBA after 2-3 years (particularly at US-focused firms like Goldman Sachs, Morgan Stanley). Australian firms are more flexible – some analysts promoted directly to Associate without MBA, others go to business school.

=== Year 3-5: Associate

*Role Evolution*
- Direct client communication and relationship development
- Leading execution work streams on transactions
- Managing analyst teams on deals
- Contributing to new business development
- Taking commercial responsibility for deal outcomes

*Technical Specialization*
- Deep sector expertise (healthcare, resources, financial services, TMT, etc.)
- Product specialization (M&A, ECM, DCM, or cross-product)
- Developing distinctive personal brand and deal experience

=== Year 5-7: Vice President (VP)

*Stepping Up*
- Client relationship ownership for mid-tier clients
- Deal economics understanding (fees, pricing, profitability)
- Coaching and developing analysts and associates
- Contributing to firm strategy and business development
- Taking accountability for deal execution quality

=== Year 7-10: Director / Executive Director

*Senior Leadership*
- Large client relationship ownership
- Originating new business and winning mandates
- Team leadership and talent development
- Firm-wide contribution (recruiting, training, thought leadership)

=== Year 10+: Managing Director / Partner

*Ultimate Responsibility*
- P&L accountability for business unit or sector
- Major client relationships and CEO/Board-level access
- Firm governance and strategic direction
- Brand building and market positioning
- Compensation heavily performance-based (deal fees, team revenue)

